<div class="slideshow-container">

    <!-- Slide 1: Title and Core Definition -->
    <div class="slide active" data-slide="1">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-red-600 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-3 mb-6">Day 3: Philosophical Justification</h1>
        <h2 class="text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">Opening (15 minutes)</h2>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-4">Recap: The Three-Day Process</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc ml-8 space-y-2">
            <li><span class="font-bold">Day 1 (Analysis):</span> Breaking down concepts (Deduction).</li>
            <li><span class="font-bold">Day 2 (Abstraction):</span> Building universal concepts from specific observations (Induction).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6">Definition: Justification is Testing</h3>
        <div class="definition">
            <span class="font-bold">Justification</span> is the final step where you take the abstract concepts you built on Day 2 and test them against a complex dilemma. The goal is to <span class="font-bold">defend your chosen concept</span> by showing why it is the most logical or ethical choice in a moment of conflict.
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-4">In other words: Justification is using Analysis (Day 1) to defend your Abstraction (Day 2).</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Slide 2: The Core Conflict: Consequence vs. Duty -->
    <div class="slide" data-slide="2">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-red-600 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-3 mb-6">Lesson Proper: Two Ways to Justify</h1>
        <h2 class="text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">When Concepts Clash, We Choose a Framework</h2>
        <p>In ethics, there are two primary ways to justify a decision, especially when concepts conflict:</p>

        <div class="concept-box bg-green-50 mt-5">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-green-700">1. Consequentialism (The Outcome)</h3>
            <p>The morality of an action is judged entirely by its result. The ends justify the means.</p>
            <ul class="list-disc ml-6 space-y-1 mt-2">
                <li><span class="font-bold">Example:</span> Utilitarianism (The "Greater Good" concept from Day 2).</li>
                <li><span class="italic text-sm">Justification is based on calculating the most positive outcome for the largest number of people.</span></li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box bg-yellow-50 mt-5">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-yellow-700">2. Deontology (The Rule/Duty)</h3>
            <p>The morality of an action is judged by whether the action itself is right or wrong, regardless of the outcome.</p>
            <ul class="list-disc ml-6 space-y-1 mt-2">
                <li><span class="font-bold">Example:</span> "Fairness" (similar to the concept from Day 2).</li>
                <li><span class="italic text-sm">Justification is based on adhering to absolute rules or duties (e.g., "Do not lie," "Do not murder").</span></li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Slide 3: Worked Example - The Trolley Problem -->
    <div class="slide" data-slide="3">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-red-600 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-3 mb-6">Worked Example: The Trolley Dilemma</h1>
        <h2 class="text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">Scenario: The Clashing Concepts</h2>
        <p class="font-semibold">A runaway trolley is heading toward five track workers. You are standing next to a lever. If you pull the lever, the trolley will switch tracks, killing one person instead of five.</p>
        <p class="mt-4">In this situation, you are forced to justify which abstract concept is superior.</p>

        <p class="mt-8"><span class="font-bold">Question 1:</span> What abstract concept is used to justify pulling the lever (killing one to save five)?</p>
        <p class="fill-in text-lg mt-2">G _ _ _ _ _ _ G _ _ D</p>
        <button class="reveal-button" onclick="revealAnswer('answer3-q1')">Reveal Utilitarian Concept</button>
        <div id="answer3-q1" class="answer-box hidden">
            <span class="font-bold">Concept:</span> GREATER GOOD (Utilitarianism)
        </div>
        
        <p class="mt-5"><span class="font-bold">Question 2:</span> What concept justifies *not* pulling the lever (allowing the five to die) because your direct action of murder is always wrong?</p>
        <p class="fill-in text-lg mt-2">M _ R _ L D _ T _</p>
        <button class="reveal-button" onclick="revealAnswer('answer3-q2')">Reveal Deontological Concept</button>
        <div id="answer3-q2" class="answer-box hidden">
            <span class="font-bold">Concept:</span> MORAL DUTY (Deontology)
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Slide 4: Group Work - The Vaccine Dilemma -->
    <div class="slide" data-slide="4">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-red-600 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-3 mb-6">Group Work: Scenario - The Secret</h1>
        <h2 class="text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">Dilemma: Saving Millions vs. Absolute Honesty</h2>
        <p class="font-semibold">A pharmaceutical company has developed a vaccine that will save hundreds of millions of lives worldwide. However, the lead doctor discovers the vaccine causes a small, permanent, non-fatal side effect in exactly 10 children.</p>
        
        <p class="mt-4">The doctor must choose: Announce the vaccine immediately (saving millions) while covering up the side effect, or delay the vaccine release by years to fix the flaw (risking millions of deaths in the meantime).</p>
        
        <p class="mt-8 font-semibold">Option A (Cover-up): Justified by Consequentialism.</p>
        <p class="mt-2"><span class="font-bold">Q1 (Concept):</span> Justifying the cover-up requires accepting a: <span class="fill-in">S _ C _ _ _ C E</span></p>
        <button class="reveal-button" onclick="revealAnswer('answer4-q1')">Reveal Concept for Option A</button>
        <div id="answer4-q1" class="answer-box hidden">
            <span class="font-bold">Concept:</span> SACRIFICE
        </div>

        <p class="mt-5 font-semibold">Option B (Reveal Flaw): Justified by Deontology.</p>
        <p class="mt-2"><span class="font-bold">Q2 (Concept):</span> Justifying the delay requires upholding the absolute rule of: <span class="fill-in">T _ _ T H</span></p>
        <button class="reveal-button" onclick="revealAnswer('answer4-q2')">Reveal Concept for Option B</button>
        <div id="answer4-q2" class="answer-box hidden">
            <span class="font-bold">Concept:</span> TRUTH
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Slide 5: Exit Ticket - REVISED -->
    <div class="slide" data-slide="5">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-red-600 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-3 mb-6">Evaluating Learning (20 minutes)</h1>
        <h2 class="text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">Exit Ticket: Justification in Conflict</h2>
        <p class="text-lg mb-6">You have now completed the three core skills of philosophical thinking:</p>
        
        <ul class="list-disc ml-8 space-y-2 font-semibold text-gray-800">
            <li>Day 1: Analysis (Deduction - Breaking down rules)</li>
            <li>Day 2: Abstraction (Induction - Building new rules)</li>
            <li>Day 3: Justification (Testing and defending rules in conflict)</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mt-10 font-bold text-xl text-red-700">Exit Ticket: Justifying the Action</p>
        <div class="concept-box bg-red-100 border-red-400 p-5 mt-4">
            <p class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Dilemma: The Scholarship Opportunity</p>
            <p class="text-base mb-4">You desperately need a top score on an upcoming <span class="font-bold">college entrance exam</span> to secure a scholarship that will cover your entire tuition, which your family cannot afford. <span class="font-bold text-red-700">The scholarship is a matter of family survival.</span> Your father is disabled from a car accident and your mother works a limited salary due to a chronic illness, making you the functional breadwinner. You know you will fail for certain because key subjects were <span class="font-bold">not covered in your 11th-grade curriculum.</span> You discover a cheat sheet accidentally left by the proctor. You know using it guarantees the scholarship, but it violates the rule of academic honesty (Moral Duty).</p>
            <p class="text-lg">Write a 3-5 sentence reflection justifying your decision to either use the cheat sheet (Consequentialism) or report it (Deontology), using the frameworks discussed today.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Navigation Buttons -->
    <div class="nav-buttons">
        <button id="prevBtn" onclick="changeSlide(-1)" class="bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700">Previous</button>
        <button id="nextBtn" onclick="changeSlide(1)" class="bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700">Next</button>
    </div>

</div>

<script>
    let slideIndex = 1;
    
    window.onload = function() {
        showSlides(slideIndex);
    };

    function changeSlide(n) {
        slideIndex += n;
        showSlides(slideIndex);
    }

    function showSlides(n) {
        const slides = document.getElementsByClassName("slide");
        const prevBtn = document.getElementById("prevBtn");
        const nextBtn = document.getElementById("nextBtn");
        const totalSlides = slides.length;

        if (n > totalSlides) {
            slideIndex = totalSlides;
        }    
        if (n < 1) {
            slideIndex = 1;
        }
        
        for (let i = 0; i < slides.length; i++) {
            slides[i].classList.remove('active');  
        }
        
        slides[slideIndex - 1].classList.add('active');

        if (slideIndex === 1) {
            prevBtn.classList.add('hidden');
        } else {
            prevBtn.classList.remove('hidden');
        }

        if (slideIndex === totalSlides) {
            nextBtn.classList.add('hidden');
        } else {
            nextBtn.classList.remove('hidden');
        }
    }

    function revealAnswer(id) {
        const element = document.getElementById(id);
        if (element.classList.contains('hidden')) {
            element.classList.remove('hidden');
            element.style.display = 'block';
            element.style.visibility = 'visible';
        } else {
            element.classList.add('hidden');
            element.style.display = 'none';
            element.style.visibility = 'hidden';
        }
    }
</script>

</body>
